%S A392893 1,52,4928,498193,49971990,4999618896,499995188365,49999941895311,
%T A392893 4999999318929402,499999992189321735,49999999911893142222
%N A392893 Number of distinct nonempty substrings in the first 10^n digits of the decimal expansion of Pi.
%H A392893 Sean A. Irvine, <a href="https://github.com/archmageirvine/joeis/blob/master/src/irvine/oeis/a392/A392893.java">Java program</a> (github)
%e A392893 To compute a(1), we form all nonempty substrings of length <= 10 and count the distinct ones:
%e A392893    1 digit,  7 distinct substrings: 3,1,4,5,9,2,6 (the repeated 1, 5 and 3 are excluded);
%e A392893    2 digits, 9 distinct substrings: 31,14,41,15,59,92,26,65,53;
%e A392893    3 digits, 8 distinct substrings: 314,141,415,159,592,926,265,653;
%e A392893    4 digits, 7 distinct substrings: 3141,1415,4159,1592,5926,9265,2653;
%e A392893    5 digits, 6 distinct substrings: 31415,14159,41592,15926,59265,92653;
%e A392893    6 digits, 5 distinct substrings: 314159,141592,415926,159265,592653;
%e A392893    7 digits, 4 distinct substrings: 3141592,1415926,4159265,1592653;
%e A392893    8 digits, 3 distinct substrings: 31415926,14159265,41592653;
%e A392893    9 digits, 2 distinct substrings: 314159265,141592653;
%e A392893   10 digits, 1 distinct substring:  3141592653.
%e A392893 Therefore, a(1) = 7+9+8+7+6+5+4+3+2+1 = 52.
